KNOWLEDGE GRAPH CONSISTENCY
Avoiding Contradictions in Large Graphs
================================================================================

Knowledge graphs (KGs) encode entities, relations, and facts as nodes + edges
(or higher-order structures). At small scale they are easy to keep coherent.
At large scale—millions to billions of triples, multi-source ingestion,
continuous updates, probabilistic extraction, multi-modal data—they become
contradiction engines. Contradictions are not bugs; they are the default state.
The engineering and theoretical problem is detecting, containing, resolving,
or deliberately preserving them without collapsing the graph into noise or
forcing false synthesis.

