In large production KGs (Google KG, Wikidata, Amazon Product Graph, enterprise
master data graphs, scientific KGs), all of the above coexist permanently.

2. CONSISTENCY DIMENSIONS
(What “Consistent” Actually Means)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Classical logic consistency (no model exists) is too strong and usually useless.
Practical consistency is multi-dimensional:

  • Hard logical consistency
    No pair of triples that directly violate a constraint (disjointness,
    functional properties, cardinality, OWL/SHACL axioms).

  • Soft / statistical consistency
    Distributional regularities (most people have one birth date; most cities
    have one primary name in a language).

  • Temporal consistency
    No future facts before past facts; proper interval algebra or Allen relations.

  • Provenance / trust consistency
    Higher-trust sources override lower-trust ones under defined rules.

  • Contextual / multi-world consistency
    Different named graphs / contexts / possible worlds can hold contradictory
    facts; the meta-graph remains coherent.

  • Identity consistency
    SameAs / SameAs clusters are transitive, symmetric, and do not create
    type clashes.

  • Paraconsistent / multi-valued consistency
    Explicitly allow contradictions and track them (see §5).

The historian’s burden maps almost directly onto the last two: maintain parallel
truths with their internal logics and refuse forced synthesis.

3. DETECTION TECHNIQUES (SCALABLE)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

A. Constraint-based (symbolic)
   • SHACL / ShEx shapes + SPARQL queries for closed-world checks.
   • OWL 2 RL/EL reasoners (or approximate ones) for open-world inconsistency
     detection.
   • Custom integrity constraints: functional properties (birthDate functional),
     inverse functional (hasSSN), disjoint classes, property chains, qualified
     cardinality.
   • Incremental maintenance: only re-check the local neighborhood of changed
     triples (dependency graph + change logs).

B. Embedding / statistical
   • Knowledge graph embedding models (TransE, RotatE, ComplEx, TuckER, etc.)
     + anomaly detection on scoring functions. High-scoring conflicting triples
     surface candidates.
   • Graph neural networks trained to predict “is this triple plausible given
     the local structure?”
   • Contrastive or multi-view embeddings that learn separate representations
     for different contexts/sources.
   • Density-based or isolation-forest methods on node/edge feature vectors
     derived from the graph.

C. Hybrid & large-scale practical
   • Materialized views + differential computation: Precompute common constraint
     patterns; only recompute deltas.
   • Streaming / windowed checks: For continuous ingestion pipelines (Flink,
     Kafka Streams + graph store).
   • Sampling + stratification: Full scan is impossible; sample by high-degree
     nodes, high-trust sources, or recent changes.
   • Probabilistic soft logic / Markov Logic Networks (scaled versions) or
     Probabilistic Soft Logic for graded inconsistency.
   • LLM-assisted verification (2024–2026 practice): Use a strong model as a
     judge on candidate contradiction pairs with retrieved local subgraph +
     provenance. High precision, still needs human or secondary model
     confirmation for high-stakes edges.

D. Identity-specific
   • Blocking + pairwise similarity + clustering (Canopy, LSH, hierarchical)
     followed by constraint propagation inside clusters.
   • Collective entity resolution that jointly optimizes links and type
     consistency.

4. RESOLUTION STRATEGIES
(What to Do Once Detected)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Delete / retract
   (rare for high-value data; usually only for clear extraction errors).

2. Prefer by provenance / trust / recency / authority
   Explicit preference rules or learned ranking (source reliability models,
   PageRank-like on citation graphs, temporal decay).

3. Contextualize / reify
   Move conflicting triples into named graphs or reified statements with
   provenance quads.
   Classic pattern:
     :Statement1 a rdf:Statement ;
       rdf:subject :Einstein ;
       rdf:predicate :birthPlace ;
       rdf:object :Ulm ;
       :accordingTo :SourceA ;
       :validFrom "1879" .

4. Create multi-valued / qualified properties
   birthPlace becomes a list or a set of qualified values with confidence/context.

5. Split the entity
   (when identity resolution failed).

6. Merge with conflict markers
   Keep both, attach a owl:incompatibleWith or custom contradicts edge, and
   surface the conflict to consumers.

7. Paraconsistent or multi-world retention
   (recommended for historiography, science, law, multi-perspective KGs)
   • Keep all claims.
   • Maintain a meta-layer of “possible worlds,” “contexts,” or “lenses.”
   • Query-time resolution: user/application supplies a context filter or
     preference order.
   • This directly implements “parallel truths with internal logic; refuse
     forced synthesis.”

