6. THEORETICAL & RELATIONAL NOTES
(Relevant to RDG / Closure Frameworks)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Large KGs are not static relational structures; they are flux systems under
continuous ingestion and query load. Consistency can be reframed relationally:

  • A contradiction is a local closure failure or an over-constrained relational
    circuit.
  • Multi-context = multiple parallel closure operators or multiple “possible
    worlds” generated by different relational engines.
  • The “Historian’s Burden” architecture is essentially a knowledge-graph
    consistency policy: maintain parallel coherent subgraphs (each with its own
    internal relational closure) and a meta-layer that tracks irreconcilable
    differences without collapsing them.
  • Detection can be expressed as searching for forced negative drift or I-spikes
    under different S/I/D modes when the same relational query is run under
    competing contexts.
  • Resolution policies become different Flux Closure Engine (FCE) topologies
    or different preference orderings on the meta-graph.

In short: the engineering problem of KG consistency and the theoretical problem
of maintaining parallel truths without forced synthesis are the same problem at
different levels of abstraction.

7. PRACTICAL RECOMMENDATIONS (2026 STATE OF PRACTICE)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

  • Never aim for global classical consistency on a multi-source, continuously
    updated KG. Aim for local consistency + global multi-context coherence +
    explicit contradiction surfaces.

  • Invest heavily in provenance and named graphs from day one. Retrofitting
    is painful.

  • Use SHACL + incremental reasoners for the hard core; statistical/LLM judges
    for the long tail.

  • Expose contradiction and confidence to downstream consumers rather than
    silently resolving.

  • For domains that match multi-perspective knowledge (history, scientific
    paradigms, etc.), treat contradiction retention as a first-class feature,
    not a failure mode.

  • Monitor the contradiction rate and resolution latency as first-class SLOs
    alongside query latency and freshness.

